## ðŸ“– Overview

Intestinal Parasites (Ji Chong) is a distinct pattern in TCM, primarily affecting the Small Intestine, but also involving the Spleen and Stomach. It is considered a Mixed Excess-Deficiency pattern: the parasites themselves represent an Excess pathogenic factor, while their presence almost invariably arises from and contributes to an underlying Deficiency of the host's righteous Qi (Zheng Qi), particularly Spleen Qi.

The parasites consume the body's vital substances (Qi, Blood, and nutrients), leading to malnutrition, a sallow complexion, and fatigue. Simultaneously, their physical presence obstructs the flow of Qi in the intestines, causing intermittent, often colicky, abdominal pain. Diagnosis is confirmed by specific signs related to the type of worm, such as anal itching (pinworms), strange cravings (hookworms), or visual confirmation of worms.

